# Project Sarthi - Technical Design Document

## Chapter 5 - Analysis Engine & Insight Generation

---

### 1. Introduction

The Project Graph represents everything Project Sarthi knows about a software project.

However, a graph by itself is only structured data.

The Analysis Engine is responsible for transforming that data into understanding.

This is where Project Sarthi becomes significantly different from a repository browser or architecture visualizer.

The parser answers:

> "What exists?"

The Project Graph answers:

> "How are things connected?"

The Analysis Engine answers:

> "What does this mean?"

Every insight shown to the user originates from this engine.

---

### 2. Responsibilities

The Analysis Engine has five primary responsibilities.

1. Analyze the completed Project Graph.
2. Detect meaningful relationships.
3. Generate project health metrics.
4. Produce contextual summaries.
5. Prepare data for visualizations.

The Analysis Engine never parses source code.

It only works with the Project Graph.

---

### 3. Position in the Architecture

The complete backend pipeline now becomes:

```text
GitHub Repository
        │
        ▼
Clone Repository
        │
        ▼
Parser Engine
        │
        ▼
Normalized Parser Output
        │
        ▼
Graph Builder
        │
        ▼
Project Graph
        │
        ▼
Analysis Engine
        │
        ▼
Insights
        │
        ▼
Database
        │
        ▼
Frontend
```

The frontend never directly analyzes code.

Everything displayed has already been processed by the backend.

---

### 4. Design Philosophy

The Analysis Engine follows one simple principle.

It should answer questions that developers repeatedly ask themselves.

Examples include:

* What changed?
* What depends on this?
* Where should I continue?
* What looks risky?
* What documentation is outdated?
* Which module is becoming too complex?

The engine should not overwhelm users with statistics.

Every insight must help someone make a better engineering decision.

---

### 5. Categories of Analysis

Version 1 divides all analysis into six categories.

#### Structural Analysis

Understands how the software is organized.

Examples:

* Number of modules.
* Number of routes.
* Number of services.
* Number of database models.
* Module hierarchy.

This information powers the Project Overview page.

---

#### Dependency Analysis

Determines how different parts of the project interact.

Examples:

Which services use this database model?

Which routes use JWT middleware?

Which frontend pages consume this endpoint?

Which modules depend on the Authentication module?

This becomes the basis for the Dependency Graph.

---

#### Documentation Analysis

Compares documentation against implementation.

Possible findings:

Documented route no longer exists.

Existing route has no documentation.

Documentation references renamed modules.

README mentions features that are missing.

Initially these checks should remain conservative to avoid false positives.

---

#### Complexity Analysis

Detects areas that are becoming difficult to maintain.

Version 1 metrics may include:

Large files.

Large modules.

Highly connected services.

Circular dependencies.

Services with many consumers.

Modules containing unusually high numbers of routes.

The goal is to identify potential maintenance risks rather than enforce coding style.

---

#### Consistency Analysis

Checks whether different parts of the project agree with each other.

Examples:

Frontend calls API that no longer exists.

OpenAPI specification differs from implementation.

Markdown documentation references removed endpoints.

Missing environment variables.

Orphan controllers.

Unused middleware.

---

#### Historical Analysis

Compares the current Project Graph with previous graph versions.

Possible insights:

New module introduced.

Routes removed.

Dependencies increased.

Database schema changed.

Documentation coverage improved.

Version 1 only stores this information.

Advanced historical visualization is intentionally postponed.

---

### 6. Insight Generation

An insight is a human-readable observation produced from graph analysis.

Every insight contains:

Title

Description

Severity

Related entities

Recommended navigation target

Example:

Title:

Authentication documentation is outdated.

Description:

The Authentication module contains four implemented routes but only two are documented.

Severity:

Medium

Navigation Target:

Authentication Module

Insights should always point users toward something actionable.

---

### 7. Project Health

Project Health is not a percentage.

Instead, it is a collection of engineering signals.

Version 1 includes:

Documentation Coverage

Dependency Complexity

Module Size

Circular Dependencies

Unused Routes

Unused Middleware

Missing Environment Variables

Disconnected Documentation

Each signal receives its own score.

The frontend may later combine these into an overall health indicator.

---

### 8. Resume Session

Resume Session is one of the defining features of Project Sarthi.

When a project is reopened after a previous analysis, the Analysis Engine prepares a contextual briefing.

Example:

Last analyzed:

12 days ago

Repository changes:

18 commits

New APIs:

3

Removed APIs:

1

Modified Modules:

Authentication

Orders

Inventory

Potential Issues:

Documentation for Orders module is now outdated.

Suggested Starting Point:

Review the Orders module because it has changed significantly since your previous analysis.

The purpose is not to summarize Git history.

The purpose is to restore the developer's mental context.

---

### 9. Navigation Recommendations

The Analysis Engine should guide exploration.

Example recommendations include:

Most recently modified module.

Largest module.

Least documented module.

Most interconnected module.

Module with highest dependency growth.

These recommendations help users decide where to begin.

---

### 10. Risk Detection

Project Sarthi is not a debugger.

However, it can identify areas that deserve additional attention.

Examples include:

Service used by many modules.

Database model referenced by many services.

Highly connected middleware.

Large dependency chains.

Circular dependencies.

Missing validation middleware.

These are engineering risks rather than confirmed bugs.

The UI should communicate this distinction clearly.

---

### 11. Why This Is Useful

Developers rarely struggle because they cannot read code.

They struggle because they cannot immediately determine where to look.

The Analysis Engine reduces exploration time by highlighting important areas before the developer begins reading source files.

This supports the central promise of Project Sarthi:

Help developers understand software before they modify it.

---

### 12. Analysis Results

Every analysis produces a structured report.

Version 1 stores:

Project Summary

Module Summaries

Dependency Statistics

Health Metrics

Generated Insights

Warnings

Graph Version

Analysis Timestamp

These results are persisted and reused by the frontend.

---

### 13. Performance Strategy

Analysis should remain responsive even for medium-sized repositories.

Initial strategies include:

Run analysis after graph construction only.

Reuse graph instead of reparsing.

Separate parsing from analysis.

Cache future graph versions.

Run independent analyses in parallel where possible.

Heavy computations should never block the frontend.

---

### 14. Future Expansion

The architecture intentionally leaves room for more advanced analyses.

Examples include:

Impact Analysis

"If I modify this service, what will likely be affected?"

Architecture Drift

"How has the project's structure evolved over time?"

Code Hotspots

"Which files change together most frequently?"

Test Coverage Visualization

"Which critical modules have insufficient tests?"

Runtime Correlation

"Which frequently failing endpoints correspond to highly coupled modules?"

These analyses build upon the existing Project Graph and require no architectural redesign.

---

### 15. Relationship with AI

The Analysis Engine must remain completely deterministic.

Its output should never depend on an AI model.

Future AI features will consume:

Project Graph

Analysis Results

Project Metadata

This approach allows AI to explain existing insights rather than invent new ones.

The platform remains fully functional without AI.

---

### 16. Engineering Principles

The Analysis Engine should never guess.

Every insight must be traceable to information contained within the Project Graph.

Every warning should be reproducible.

Every recommendation should be explainable.

Trust is more important than feature count.

Project Sarthi should occasionally report fewer insights if that means every reported insight is accurate, understandable and genuinely useful.

