# Project Sarthi - Technical Design Document

## Chapter 11 – GitHub Integration & Repository Analysis Workflow

---

### 1. Introduction

Repository analysis is the primary workflow of Project Sarthi.

Everything else in the application depends upon it.

Whenever a user imports a project, Sarthi transforms a GitHub repository into an interactive understanding of the software.

This transformation follows a deterministic pipeline.

Every repository is processed using the same sequence of stages.

This guarantees predictable behaviour and simplifies debugging.

---

### 2. Design Philosophy

Repository analysis should satisfy the following principles.

* The repository remains the source of truth.
* Analysis is repeatable.
* Analysis is deterministic.
* No source code is modified.
* Source code is never executed.
* Partial analysis is preferred over failed analysis.

The user should be able to trust that repeated analyses of the same commit produce identical Project Graphs.

---

### 3. High-Level Workflow

The complete workflow is shown below.

```text
User clicks "Analyze Project"

        │

        ▼

Validate Request

        │

        ▼

Clone / Update Repository

        │

        ▼

Detect Technologies

        │

        ▼

Load Compatible Plugins

        │

        ▼

Parse Repository

        │

        ▼

Generate Normalized Output

        │

        ▼

Build Project Graph

        │

        ▼

Validate Graph

        │

        ▼

Run Analysis Engine

        │

        ▼

Persist Results

        │

        ▼

Mark Analysis Complete

        │

        ▼

Frontend Fetches Latest Results
```

Every stage is independent.

Failures should remain isolated whenever possible.

---

### 4. Step 1 – Request Validation

Before analysis begins, the backend verifies:

* User is authenticated.
* Project exists.
* User owns the project.
* Repository URL is valid.

If validation fails, analysis does not begin.

---

### 5. Step 2 – Repository Synchronization

The Repository Service determines whether the repository already exists locally.

If the repository has not been cloned:

Clone repository.

Otherwise:

Pull latest changes from the default branch.

This minimizes unnecessary downloads.

Temporary repository location:

```text
temp/

repositories/

<project-id>/
```

Version 1 stores repositories temporarily.

Future versions may introduce configurable caching.

---

### 6. Step 3 – Technology Detection

The Technology Detector scans the repository.

Detection relies on project files rather than executing code.

Examples include:

Package dependencies.

Configuration files.

Directory structure.

Recognized technologies:

* React
* Next.js
* Express
* Prisma
* Mongoose
* Markdown
* OpenAPI

The detector returns a Technology Report.

Example:

```text
React

✓

Express

✓

Prisma

✓

Markdown

✓

OpenAPI

✗
```

This report determines which parser plugins will be loaded.

---

### 7. Step 4 – Plugin Initialization

The Parser Manager receives the Technology Report.

It loads only compatible plugins.

Example:

```text
Repository

↓

Technology Report

↓

Express Parser

↓

React Parser

↓

Prisma Parser

↓

Markdown Parser
```

Unused plugins are never initialized.

This keeps analysis efficient.

---

### 8. Step 5 – File Collection

Each parser identifies the files it needs.

Examples:

React Parser

* .tsx
* .jsx

Express Parser

* routes
* controllers
* services

Prisma Parser

* schema.prisma

Markdown Parser

* README.md
* *.md

The Parser Manager merges these file lists while preventing duplicate work.

---

### 9. Step 6 – Static Parsing

Each parser converts its files into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST).

From these trees it extracts:

Entities.

Relationships.

Metadata.

No parser communicates directly with another parser.

Every parser works independently.

---

### 10. Step 7 – Normalized Parser Output

Parser results are converted into a shared intermediate format.

Example:

```text
Route

POST /login

Controller

LoginController

Service

AuthService

Database Model

User
```

This normalized format is intentionally framework-independent.

It becomes the input to the Graph Builder.

---

### 11. Step 8 – Graph Construction

The Graph Builder performs several responsibilities.

Create nodes.

Create edges.

Assign identifiers.

Merge duplicates.

Validate references.

Generate Project Graph.

At this point the application has an internal understanding of the software.

No insights have been generated yet.

---

### 12. Step 9 – Graph Validation

Before continuing, the graph is validated.

Validation checks include:

Duplicate nodes.

Duplicate edges.

Invalid relationships.

Orphan entities.

Missing modules.

Invalid references.

Validation failures are logged.

Recoverable issues should not terminate analysis.

---

### 13. Step 10 – Analysis

The Analysis Engine receives the validated Project Graph.

It produces:

Project Overview.

Module summaries.

Dependency statistics.

Project Health.

Insights.

Warnings.

Resume Session data.

Everything generated here is deterministic.

---

### 14. Step 11 – Database Persistence

The following information is stored.

Project metadata.

Graph Version.

Nodes.

Edges.

Analysis.

Insights.

Health Metrics.

Only after persistence succeeds should the analysis be considered complete.

---

### 15. Step 12 – Cleanup

Temporary resources should be cleaned.

Version 1 strategy:

Keep cloned repository for future analyses.

Remove temporary parsing artefacts.

Release memory.

Future versions may introduce configurable repository retention policies.

---

### 16. Frontend Progress Tracking

The frontend should continuously display analysis progress.

Backend stages include:

```text
Queued

↓

Cloning Repository

↓

Detecting Technologies

↓

Loading Plugins

↓

Parsing Files

↓

Building Project Graph

↓

Analyzing Graph

↓

Saving Results

↓

Completed
```

The frontend polls the analysis status endpoint every few seconds.

This provides transparency without requiring WebSockets.

---

### 17. Failure Recovery

Failures should stop only the affected stage whenever possible.

Examples:

Repository cannot be cloned.

Analysis terminates immediately.

Markdown parser fails.

Continue with remaining parsers.

OpenAPI specification missing.

Skip OpenAPI parser.

Graph validation warning.

Continue analysis while recording warnings.

The objective is graceful degradation.

---

### 18. Performance Considerations

Initial optimization strategies:

Ignore:

* node_modules
* dist
* build
* coverage
* generated files

Process parser plugins independently.

Avoid reparsing identical graph versions in future releases.

Store graph versions separately.

Future versions may introduce incremental parsing.

---

### 19. Security Considerations

Repository analysis must never execute user code.

Additional precautions:

Clone into isolated directories.

Validate repository URLs.

Reject repositories exceeding configured limits.

Reject unsupported archive formats.

Sanitize Markdown before rendering.

Never expose local filesystem paths.

Only static analysis is permitted.

---

### 20. Sequence Diagram

The complete interaction is summarized below.

```text
Frontend

↓

POST /analyze

↓

Backend

↓

Repository Service

↓

Technology Detector

↓

Parser Manager

↓

Parser Plugins

↓

Graph Builder

↓

Analysis Engine

↓

Database

↓

Status = Completed

↓

Frontend fetches Overview

↓

User begins exploration
```

This sequence forms the backbone of Project Sarthi.

---

### 21. Engineering Decisions

#### ED-007

Repository analysis is entirely deterministic.

Reason:

Repeatable analyses improve reliability, debugging and user trust.

Status:

Accepted.

---

#### ED-008

Repositories are analyzed through static analysis only.

Reason:

Executing arbitrary repositories introduces unacceptable security risks.

Status:

Accepted.

---

#### ED-009

Only compatible parser plugins are loaded.

Reason:

Reduces memory usage, improves performance and simplifies parser maintenance.

Status:

Accepted.

---

### 22. Engineering Principles

The repository analysis workflow should feel invisible.

From the user's perspective, they provide a GitHub repository and receive an understandable software project.

All complexity—cloning, parsing, graph construction and analysis—remains hidden behind a single action.

The success of Project Sarthi depends on making this transformation reliable, predictable and fast enough that developers trust it as part of their normal workflow.

