# Project Sarthi - Technical Design Document

## Chapter 12 – Plugin Development Guide & Extensibility

---

### 1. Introduction

Project Sarthi is designed around one fundamental principle:

**The core application should understand software, not frameworks.**

Frameworks evolve.

New languages appear.

Libraries change.

The Project Graph should remain stable.

Parser plugins act as translators between specific technologies and the Project Graph.

This architecture allows Project Sarthi to grow without rewriting its core.

---

### 2. Why Plugins?

Without plugins, adding support for a new framework would require modifying:

* Parser Engine
* Graph Builder
* Analysis Engine
* Tests
* Database logic

With plugins:

Only one component changes.

The new parser.

Everything else continues to work.

This dramatically improves maintainability.

---

### 3. Core Principle

Every plugin has exactly one responsibility:

Convert framework-specific code into framework-independent information.

The parser should never concern itself with:

* UI
* Database
* Graph visualization
* Authentication
* Search
* Analysis

It simply describes what exists.

---

### 4. Responsibilities of a Plugin

Every parser plugin should:

Detect whether it supports the project.

Collect relevant files.

Parse those files.

Extract entities.

Extract relationships.

Generate normalized output.

Return the result.

Nothing more.

---

### 5. Responsibilities of the Core

The core system is responsible for:

Loading plugins.

Managing execution order.

Combining parser results.

Building the Project Graph.

Running analysis.

Persisting data.

Rendering visualizations.

This separation prevents tight coupling.

---

### 6. Plugin Lifecycle

Every parser follows the same execution flow.

```text
Repository

↓

supports()

↓

collectFiles()

↓

parse()

↓

extract()

↓

normalize()

↓

return
```

The Parser Manager coordinates this lifecycle.

---

### 7. Parser Interface

Every plugin implements a shared contract.

Conceptually:

```ts
interface ParserPlugin {

  id: string

  name: string

  version: string

  supports(project): boolean

  collectFiles(project): File[]

  parse(files): ParsedOutput

}
```

Future versions may introduce optional lifecycle hooks.

---

### 8. Normalized Output

Plugins never generate graph nodes directly.

Instead they return a normalized structure.

Example:

```text
Entity

Type

Metadata

Relationships
```

Example Route Entity

```text
Type

Route

Name

POST /login

Metadata

Method

POST

Path

/login

Relationships

handled_by

LoginController
```

Every parser returns the same structure.

The Graph Builder handles graph creation.

---

### 9. Supported Plugins (Version 1)

React Parser

Responsibilities:

Detect pages.

Detect components.

Detect API consumers.

---

Next.js Parser

Responsibilities:

Detect App Router.

Detect layouts.

Detect server/client components.

---

Express Parser

Responsibilities:

Detect routes.

Detect middleware.

Detect controllers.

Detect services.

Determine route-based modules.

---

Prisma Parser

Responsibilities:

Parse schema.

Extract models.

Extract relationships.

---

Mongoose Parser

Responsibilities:

Parse schemas.

Extract collections.

Extract relationships.

---

Markdown Parser

Responsibilities:

Parse documentation.

Extract headings.

Associate documentation.

---

OpenAPI Parser

Responsibilities:

Parse specification.

Extract endpoints.

Compare implementation.

---

### 10. Communication Rules

Plugins should never communicate with one another.

Example:

The React parser should not ask the Express parser for routes.

Instead:

React parser returns:

Frontend API usage.

Express parser returns:

Backend routes.

The Graph Builder later connects them.

This guarantees independence.

---

### 11. Error Isolation

Plugin failures should remain isolated.

Example:

OpenAPI parser fails.

↓

React parser continues.

↓

Express parser continues.

↓

Graph still builds.

↓

Warning generated.

One plugin should never compromise the entire analysis.

---

### 12. Versioning

Every parser has its own version.

Example:

```text
Express Parser

v1.0.0
```

Graph Versions record:

Parser Version

Project Version

Analysis Timestamp

This simplifies debugging.

---

### 13. Testing Plugins

Every parser should have independent test repositories.

Example:

```text
test-projects/

react-basic/

express-auth/

next-dashboard/

prisma-blog/

mongoose-api/
```

Each repository exists solely to verify parser correctness.

This greatly simplifies regression testing.

---

### 14. Development Workflow

Adding a new framework follows a predictable process.

Example:

Support NestJS.

Step 1

Create NestJS Parser.

↓

Step 2

Implement interface.

↓

Step 3

Generate normalized output.

↓

Step 4

Run parser tests.

↓

Step 5

Parser Manager loads plugin automatically.

No other architecture changes are required.

---

### 15. Why This Matters

Imagine Version 3 of Project Sarthi.

A user imports:

React

NestJS

PostgreSQL

GraphQL

Docker

Kubernetes

The core application does not know these technologies.

It only understands the Project Graph.

Parser plugins perform the translation.

This makes the architecture future-proof.

---

### 16. Plugin Directory

Recommended structure:

```text
parsers/

react/

index.ts

parser.ts

visitor.ts

extractors.ts

tests/

express/

index.ts

parser.ts

visitor.ts

extractors.ts

tests/

...
```

Every parser follows the same organization.

This improves readability.

---

### 17. Parser Design Principles

Every parser should be:

Deterministic.

Stateless.

Independent.

Fast.

Easy to test.

Easy to replace.

Avoid storing global state.

Everything required for parsing should come from the repository being analyzed.

---

### 18. Engineering Decisions

#### ED-010

Parser plugins emit normalized data rather than graph nodes.

Reason:

Keeps graph creation centralized.

Status:

Accepted.

---

#### ED-011

Plugins never communicate directly.

Reason:

Prevents tight coupling and simplifies maintenance.

Status:

Accepted.

---

#### ED-012

Every parser is independently testable.

Reason:

Parser correctness directly affects every downstream feature.

Status:

Accepted.

---

### 19. Future Opportunities

The plugin system enables future support for:

NestJS

Fastify

Python

Flask

Django

Spring Boot

Laravel

Ruby on Rails

Go

Rust

Docker

Terraform

GitHub Actions

Kubernetes

GraphQL

Additional support should require writing new plugins rather than modifying existing architecture.

---

### 20. Engineering Principles

The plugin system exists to protect the architecture from growth.

As Project Sarthi evolves, the number of supported technologies will increase dramatically.

The complexity of the parser engine should not.

The success of the architecture will be measured by how easy it is to support a completely new framework five years from now without modifying the core application.

